Sparkify Project Workspace¶

Introduction¶

It's critical for any service provider to survive if they can sense that some of their users are about to leave or cancel their service. In this project, we are provided with dataset contain logs recorded for every user-service interaction. We will talk about detail of the dataset in later section. Our mission is to build predictive models from the dataset we owned and to predict whether a specific user has intention to churn.

To achieve our goal, we apply Pyspark as the framework of our project. Pyspark is the Spark API for Python that works efficiently especially when dealing with large size data. With the help of Spark, we are able to build highly efficient and useful applications.

Overview¶

Our goal is to use log dataset to build predictive model that predicts users intention to churn. In order to get best model. We would achieve it by analyzing some features from the dataset with Spark manipulation. Furthermore, we check that if the feature can separate churned and non-churned user effectively. Finally, we would use both f1_score and accuracy as metrics to evaluate our model because sometimes we would sacrifice one when trying to optimizing the other.

Well... Let's start the project

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Define Churn¶

We define churned users as user who had been to Cancellation Confirmation page. We also define upgrade and downgrade event when users visited Submit Upgrade or Submit Downgrade page.

In [311]:
#Define churn as user ever been to Cancellation Confirmation page
cancel_churn = udf(lambda x: 1 if x == "Cancellation Confirmation" else 0, IntegerType())
df = df.withColumn("Cancel", cancel_churn("page"))

#Define downgrade as user ever been to Submit Downgrade page
downgrade_churn = udf(lambda x: 1 if x == "Submit Downgrade" else 0, IntegerType())
df = df.withColumn("Downgrade", downgrade_churn("page"))

#Define upgrade as user ever been to Submit Upgrade page
upgrade_churn = udf(lambda x: 1 if x == "Submit Upgrade" else 0, IntegerType())
df = df.withColumn("Upgrade", upgrade_churn("page"))

Create User Time Span¶

Because some of our variable would be analyzed on a daily basis, we create a time span column that records the time length between first and last log message.

In [312]:
#Define window for time span calculation
windowSpec  = Window.partitionBy("userId")

#Create new column containing time span in days
df = df.withColumn("Time-Span", ceil((sql_func.max(col('ts')).over(windowSpec) - sql_func.min(col('ts')).over(windowSpec))/86400000))

#Create user table that check if  user has ever churned
churned_users_table = df.groupBy('userId').agg(sql_func.max('Cancel').alias('Churned'))
churned_users = list(churned_users_table.filter(churned_users_table['Churned'] == 1).select('userId').toPandas()['userId'])

#Define udf to transform user churn state
churn_or_not = udf(lambda x: 1 if x in churned_users else 0, IntegerType())
df = df.withColumn('Churned', churn_or_not('userId'))

user_Downgrade_Times.loc[user_Downgrade_Times['Churned'] == 1,'count'] /= num_churn_user

User Device Exploration¶

In [312]:
def extract_device(col):
    """
    This function extraction device from column text
    
    Input: Text content of the column
    Output: Device name
    """
    device = re.findall(r'\([a-zA-Z0-9]*',col)[0].strip()[1:]
    return device

#Define user-defined device extraction function
get_device = udf(extract_device, StringType())

#Create new column as device
df = df.withColumn('Device', get_device('userAgent'))

#Create dataframe containing information of device of churned user groups
device_user = df.groupBy(['userId','Churned']).agg(first('Device').alias('Device'))

Transform dummy variables¶

def transform(column_value):
    """
    This cell check if input matches certain category
    
    Input: Row value
    Outout: 1 if the value matches category, else 0
    """
    global category
    if column_value == category:
        return 1
    else:       
        return 0

categorical_features = []    
    
#Transform categorical columns to dummy variable columns   
for col_name in ['Final_Level']:
    categories = User_Feature_Dataframe.select(col_name).distinct().collect()
    for cat in categories[1:]:    
        category = cat[col_name]
        udfs = udf(transform, IntegerType())
        User_Feature_Dataframe = User_Feature_Dataframe.withColumn(col_name + '_' + str(category), udfs(col_name))
        categorical_features.append(col_name + '_' + str(category))

#Drop categorical columns
User_Feature_Dataframe = User_Feature_Dataframe.drop('Final_Level')

Preliminary Test¶

Because the original dataset is imbalanced and with only hundreds of data, we do a preliminary test to check how individual classifier works and decide a proper positive label to negative label ratio for later optimization

In [85]:
def evaluation(pred_table):
    """
    This function evaluation a prediction dataframe
    
    Input: A prediction dataframe
    Output: Metrics such as accuracy, recall, precision, f1_score
    """
    #Find out True Postive(TP), False Positive(FP), True Negative(TN) and False Negative(FN)
    TP = pred_table.filter((pred_table.label == 1)&(pred_table.prediction == 1)).count()
    FP = pred_table.filter((pred_table.label == 0)&(pred_table.prediction == 1)).count()
    TN = pred_table.filter((pred_table.label == 0)&(pred_table.prediction == 0)).count()
    FN = pred_table.filter((pred_table.label == 1)&(pred_table.prediction == 0)).count()
    
    #Calculate accuracy, recall, precision and f1_score 
    num_of_test_sample = pred_table.count()
    accuracy = (TP + TN) / num_of_test_sample
    recall = TP / (TP + FN)
    precision = TP / (TP + FP)
    f1_score = 2 * precision*recall / (precision + recall)
    
    return accuracy, recall, precision, f1_score

#Create evaluator instance and evaluation dictionary
evaluator = BinaryClassificationEvaluator(metricName='areaUnderROC')
pre_test_evaluation = {}


#training = create_balanced_table(training, 0.66)
for model_name in model_dict.keys():
    pre_test_evaluation[model_name] = {} 
    for ratio in [1.5, 1.25, 1, 0.75, 0.5]:
        print('Conducting preliminary test for {} with pos-neg ratio{}'.format(model_name, ratio))    
        metric_array = np.array([0,0,0,0,0])
        new_df = create_balanced_table(ml_data, ratio)
        for i in range(5):               
            training, test = new_df.randomSplit([0.7, 0.3], seed = i)
            model_dict[model_name]['Model'] = model_dict[model_name]['instance'].fit(training)
            pred = model_dict[model_name]['Model'].transform(test)         
            AUC = evaluator.evaluate(pred)
            acc, rec, prec, f1 = evaluation(pred)
            metric_array = metric_array + np.array([AUC, acc, rec, prec, f1])
       
        pre_test_evaluation[model_name][ratio] = metric_array/5

def create_balanced_table(df, pos_neg_ratio, add = 'negative'):
    """
    This function returns a dataset with desired positive to negative label ratio
    
    Input: Dataframe and desired positive to negative label ratio
    Output: Dataframe with desired positive to negative label ratio
    """
    num_of_pos = df.filter(df['label'] == 1).count()
    num_of_neg = df.filter(df['label'] == 0).count()
    positives = df.filter(df['label'] == 1)
    negatives = df.filter(df['label'] == 0)
    if add == 'negative':      
        to_add = negatives.orderBy(rand()).limit(round(num_of_pos/pos_neg_ratio))
        balanced_df = positives.union(to_add)
    elif add == 'positive':
        to_add = random_sampling(positives, num_of_neg*pos_neg_ratio - num_of_pos)
        positives  = positives.union(to_add)
        balanced_df = negatives.union(positives)

    return balanced_df

def random_sampling(pos_df, num_of_sampling):
    """
    This function randomly selects specific amount of samples with replacement
    
    Input: Positive labeled dataframe and desired number of selection
    Output: Dataframe after sampling
    """
    sampled_df = pos_df.orderBy(rand()).limit(1)
    sample_times = 1
    while num_of_sampling > sample_times:
        sampled_df = sampled_df.union(pos_df.orderBy(rand()).limit(1))
        sample_times += 1
    return sampled_df

#Create 4-fold crossvalidator instance

                          estimatorParamMaps = paramGrid_lr,
                          evaluator = evaluator_lr,
                          numFolds = 8)

#Fit the crossvalidator instance to training data

#Temporary dictionary for making model metrics

model_metrics = {}

#Iterate through models
for model_name in temp_dict.keys():
    
    #We first evaluate using test_balanced set
    temp_model = temp_dict[model_name].bestModel
    temp_test = temp_model.transform(test_balanced)
    AUC = evaluator.evaluate(temp_test)
    acc, rec, prec, f1 = evaluation(temp_test)
    model_metrics[model_name + "Test"] = [AUC, acc, rec, prec, f1]
    
    #Then, we also check the whole set
    temp_all = temp_model.transform(ml_data)
    AUC = evaluator.evaluate(temp_all)
    acc, rec, prec, f1 = evaluation(temp_all)
    model_metrics[model_name + "All"] = [AUC, acc, rec, prec, f1]
    
#Turn result into dataframe

Justification¶

As you see, the performance drop a lot when we analyzed the whole dataset instead of balanced dataset. Because the gradient-boosted tree can easily be overfitted in this small dataset and it's more time-consuming than Random-Forest. We deicide to take Random Forest as our final model.

Overall, Logistic Regression did the worst perhaps because we are analyzing human behavior which is not so linear.

Besides, the psosible possible reasons for gradient-boosted tree to get overfitted so easily is that the algorithm is iterative and greedy, as we only have little amount of data, it's easy to get overfitted.

The major problem causing overall failure in whole set in my opinion is due to dataset size, because the amount of data is not enough to represent population, the model could easily get biased.

Conclusion¶

Reflection¶

  • We have done tons of exploratory data analysis and found that actually most analysis does not reflect obvious difference between churned and non churned user group

  • With proper exploratory analysis, we finally chose some features that seems to be significant enough to separate churne and non churned users. Thankfully, this works but not so well and can be further improved.

  • At the beginning of machine process, we first do preliminary test to decide desirable positive to negative lable ratio to try to enhance to ability of classification because if we don't do it, the classifier may not be able to properly predict (or can even lead to one class prediction)

  • We start from three candidates-Logistic Regression, Random Forest and Graduent-Boosted Tree. The performance of Logistic regression is slightly worse than the other two. When testing using balanced test set, we can obtain accuracy close to 75% and f1 also close to 0.75. However, the performance drops a lot after testing with whole dataset.

  • Random Forest and Gradient-Boosted Tree's performance are quite similar, but it's more likely for Gradient-Boosted Tree to overfit and it's more time-consuming. We decide that Random Forest may be the better choice of final model in this project.

  • It seems it's pretty hard to further improve the model with this small dataset, we should later work on the full dataset that can really interpret general user behavior

  • From feature importance analysis, we can sayt that ratings and errors are pretty important for service provider. It's crucial for service provider to make sure their service are steady and please users that they are willing to give out positive ratings instead of negative ones.

Improvement¶

  • This dataset is just part of the huge dataset with only 400 user data. The quantity is not enough to represent population and can easily be biased.
  • The overfitting problem is quite serious especially for Gradient-Boosted Tree, but tuning parameters and decreasing feature amount does not seem to help. In my opinion, this could be relieved when we use the full dataset.
  • This dataset is imbalanced that there are much more negative label than positive ones, we have to balance the dataset first otherwise it could lead to fault prediction (all in one class)
